g.text: In most cases we start with Factory Method or Abstract Factory and evolve towards Builder in case we need more control over the construction steps and/or we want to separate the construction algorithm from the actual product.

g.title: Folded Corner.15
g.desc: The construction logic and representation are separated from ...

g.text: The construction logic and representation are separated from the client and object it-self. This gains re-usability and readability. Re-usability, because different representations can be created with the same construction logic. Readability, because we extract logic that constraints when and how a object should be created.

g.text: The separation of construction logic and representation, provide a way to extend our system with a new representation without modifying the construction logic.

g.title: Folded Corner.41
g.desc: It could be that a lot of variations are required of an objec...

g.text: It could be that a lot of variations are required of an object. To have these different variants we often implement constructor overloading with different parameter sets. This could result in pollution of the object, which makes readability harder. On top of that, it will become harder to understand and remember which constructor we need for which variant. The Builder pattern provides an abstraction to clarify intent and thus reduce complexity.

g.title: Folded Corner.44
g.desc: To achieve variation in object construction we could use sett...

g.text: To achieve variation in object construction we could use setters (JavaBeans Pattern). This overcomes the pollution created by constructor Telescoping. However, the pattern might be too flexible, resulting in a not usable product. E.g. build steps depend on others or certain build steps are mandatory. The builder pattern can ensure this safety via its director.
